Creating a simple HTML web app that displays a random public webcam stream involves using the `<iframe>` element to point to a webcam stream URL. However, keep in mind that embedding third-party streaming content can be restricted by Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) policies, and many webcam streams may not allow this kind of embedding.

Below is an example of a single HTML file that includes embedded CSS and JavaScript to create a simple interface for displaying a random webcam stream. Note that you would need to replace the example webcam URLs with actual webcam stream URLs that allow embedding.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Webcam Stream</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        #webcam {
            border: 2px solid #ccc;
            width: 80%;
            height: 500px;
            background-color: #000;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            margin: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Random Public Webcam Stream</h1>
<div id="webcam-container">
    <iframe
        id="webcam"
        src=""
        frameborder="0"
        allowfullscreen>
    </iframe>
</div>
<button id="next-stream">Next Webcam Stream</button>

<script>
    const webcamUrls = [
        "https://example.com/stream1", // Replace with actual stream URL
        "https://example.com/stream2", // Replace with actual stream URL
        "https://example.com/stream3", // Replace with actual stream URL
        // Add more URLs as needed
    ];

    function getRandomStreamUrl() {
        const randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * webcamUrls.length);
        return webcamUrls[randomIndex];
    }

    function loadRandomStream() {
        const iframe = document.getElementById('webcam');
        iframe.src = getRandomStreamUrl();
    }

    document.getElementById('next-stream').onclick = loadRandomStream;

    // Load the first random stream when the page loads
    window.onload = loadRandomStream;
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Replace the placeholder URLs in the `webcamUrls` array with actual public webcam stream URLs that can be embedded.
2. You can add additional URLs to the array as needed.
3. Save this code in an HTML file and open it in a web browser to test the functionality.

This simple web app will show a random webcam stream and allow you to refresh it to display another random stream by clicking the "Next Webcam Stream" button. Just ensure that the streams you use are compliant with embedding rules.

Certainly! Below is an HTML file that contains embedded CSS and JavaScript. The "Next Webcam Stream" button generates a random URL with a six-digit number appended to the base URL `http://www.insecam.org/en/view/`. When clicked, it will load the corresponding webcam stream in the iframe.

Here's the complete code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Random Public Webcam Stream</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            text-align: center;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
        }
        #webcam {
            border: 2px solid #ccc;
            width: 80%;
            height: 500px;
            background-color: #000;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            margin: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Random Public Webcam Stream</h1>
<div id="webcam-container">
    <iframe
        id="webcam"
        src=""
        frameborder="0"
        allowfullscreen>
    </iframe>
</div>
<button id="next-stream">Next Webcam Stream</button>

<script>
    function getRandomStreamUrl() {
        const randomNumber = Math.floor(100000 + Math.random() * 900000); // Generate a random 6-digit number
        return `http://www.insecam.org/en/view/${randomNumber}/`;
    }

    function loadRandomStream() {
        const iframe = document.getElementById('webcam');
        iframe.src = getRandomStreamUrl(); // Update iframe source to the new URL
    }

    document.getElementById('next-stream').onclick = loadRandomStream;

    // Load the first random stream when the page loads
    window.onload = loadRandomStream;
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Instructions:
1. Save the code above into an HTML file (for example, `webcam_stream.html`).
2. Open the HTML file in a web browser.
3. Each time you click the "Next Webcam Stream" button, it will generate a random six-digit number and load the webcam stream URL in the iframe.

Remember to ensure that the generated URLs point to accessible webcam streams. If the numbers do not correspond to actual streams available on the specified site, you may see a "not found" message or a blank iframe.
